SIMPLE: summit
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Summit
<hw>Sum"mit</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>sommet</ets>,
dim. of OF. <ets>som</ets>, <ets>sum</ets>, top, from L.
<ets>summum</ets>, from <ets>summus</ets> highest. See <er>Sum</er>,
<pos>n.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The top; the highest
point.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Fixed on the <qex>summit</qex> of the highest mount.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The highest degree; the utmost elevation; the acme;
<as>as, the <ex>summit</ex> of human fame</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The most elevated part of a
bivalve shell, or the part in which the hinge is situated.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Summit level</b></col>, <cd>the highest level of a canal,
a railroad, or the like, in surmounting an ascent.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Summitless</ent>⟦br⟧
